{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"705a6fe5-24dc-4102-80b7-3ba40e886cde","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` ties the lifetime to an **HTTP request** — each request gets a fresh instance. In MAUI, there's no equivalent request boundary. The app is one long-lived process, so without an explicit scope, `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your DbContext instance persists for the app's entire lifetime.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a new DbContext each time it's injected.\n2. **Create manual scopes** — inject `IServiceScopeFactory` and create/dispose scopes per page or operation:\n\n```csharp\nusing var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\nvar db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n```\n\n3. **Use a DbContext factory** — register with `AddDbContextFactory` and inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>`, then create short-lived contexts as needed:\n\n```csharp\nusing var db = dbContextFactory.CreateDbContext();\n```\n\nOption 3 is generally the recommended pattern for MAUI/desktop apps.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bc438961-0612-48f2-9e1e-a15d592c5ed6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common issue when transitioning from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request (each request is a \"scope\"). In MAUI, there's no equivalent of an HTTP request lifecycle — the app runs as a single long-lived process. By default, MAUI doesn't create new scopes per page navigation, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same DbContext instance lives for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":427,"requestId":"5022:63E52:1D2334A:204668D:69FA9275"},"id":"ceb6e5e9-ce5b-4f6b-a656-c19ca11ee380","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:59:44.350Z","parentId":"61ed4e52-338f-4be7-b704-ee1b50008b64"}
